{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"J. Pedro Ribeiro","author":"J. Pedro Ribeiro"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"6cbcaa5a-9f8f-51a3-98d1-c5a9d4f51b02","excerpt":"I love  Google Analytics  but the browser usage stats always annoyed me. Since modern, evergreen browsers release features very frequently, you end up having to…","html":"<p>I love <strong>Google Analytics</strong> but the browser usage stats always annoyed me. Since modern, evergreen browsers release features very frequently, you end up having to combine multiple entries into one in order to get a more usable data. For example, when identifying the users on Chrome, I really don’t care how many of them are on Chrome 48 vs 49, I only care if they are on Chrome.</p>\n<p>To solve this, I created a small <strong>Node.js</strong> app called <a href=\"https://github.com/jpedroribeiro/r2d2\">Rapid Reporting Device Dashboard</a>, or <a href=\"https://github.com/jpedroribeiro/r2d2\">r2d2</a> for short (yes I really wanted to create an r2d2 acronym).</p>\n<p>It uses the Google Analytics API to connect to your dashboard. Reads the browser stats from the last 30 days and prints out in an <em>aggregated</em> manner. The rules are, of course, very customised to my needs but the code itself is very easy to change if you need a different output.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/54651330afb95a6485635a166ce07188/6fdc2/Screen-Shot-2016-03-27-at-16.18.40.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 403px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 132.75434243176178%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"r2d2\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/54651330afb95a6485635a166ce07188/6fdc2/Screen-Shot-2016-03-27-at-16.18.40.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/54651330afb95a6485635a166ce07188/cf440/Screen-Shot-2016-03-27-at-16.18.40.png 148w,\n/static/54651330afb95a6485635a166ce07188/d2d38/Screen-Shot-2016-03-27-at-16.18.40.png 295w,\n/static/54651330afb95a6485635a166ce07188/6fdc2/Screen-Shot-2016-03-27-at-16.18.40.png 403w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 403px) 100vw, 403px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>I wrote it using some <strong>ES2015</strong> features like: <code class=\"language-text\">let, const, import</code> and <code class=\"language-text\">template strings</code>. It’s all up on <a href=\"https://github.com/jpedroribeiro/r2d2\">GitHub</a> so feel free to have a look.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Aggregating Google Analytics Browser Statistics with r2d2","date":"March 27, 2016"}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"/2016/03/aggregating-google-analytics-browser-statistics-with-r2d2/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/2016/03/web-ethics/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Web Ethics"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/2016/04/web-education/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Web Education"}}}}